er-fetching/under-fetching, boosts developer productivity with self‑documenting schemas, and supports rapid frontend development."},{"heading":"1. Schema Design","content":"Define types, queries, mutations, and enums. Use SDL (schema definition language).","code":"type User { id: ID! name: String! }\ntype Query { user(id: ID!): User }"},{"heading":"2. Resolvers & Data Fetching","content":"Write resolvers to fetch from DB or services.","code":"const user = await db.User.findById(args.id);"},{"heading":"3. Server Setup","content":"Use Apollo Server, GraphQL Yoga, or GraphQL JS.","links":[{"text":"Apollo Server Docs","href":"https://www.apollographql.com/docs/apollo-server/"}]},{"heading":"4. Integration with Frameworks","content":"Use with Node.js, Python, Ruby, Java, .NET, and frontend clients like Apollo Client or Relay."},{"heading":"5. Pagination & Filtering","content":"Implement Relay-style cursor pagination or offset-based pagination."},{"heading":"6. Authentication & Authorization","content":"Add JWT or session-based auth in resolvers. Use directives for field or schema-level security."},{"heading":"7. Error Handling & Validation","content":"Return proper error codes and validation messages via custom error types."},{"heading":"8. Batching & Caching","content":"Use DataLoader for batching; implement server-side or CDN caching."},{"heading":"9. Subscriptions & Real‑time","content":"Use WebSockets, Apollo Subscriptions, or GraphQL over MQTT.","code":"type Subscription { messageAdded: Message }"},{"heading":"10. Federation & Schema Stitching","content":"Split schemas into microservices using Apollo Federation or stitched schemas."},{"heading":"11. Performance Optimization","content":"Monitor query complexity, depth limits, and avoid N+1 queries."},{"heading":"12. Tooling & IDE Support","content":"Use GraphQL Playground, GraphiQL, Apollo Studio, GraphQL Code Generator."},{"heading":"13. Testing","content":"Write unit tests for resolvers and integration tests using mock servers."},{"heading":"14. Monitoring & Analytics","content":"Use Apollo Engine, GraphQL Inspector, tracing, and error tracking."},{"heading":"15. Deployment & Hosting","content":"Deploy on Node.js, serverless (AWS Lambda), or managed platforms like Hasura or GraphQL Mesh."},{"heading":"16. Versioning & Deprecation","content":"Use deprecation directives and evolve schema incrementally."},{"heading":"17. Security Best Practices","content":"Validate input, disable introspection in production, limit complexity, and enforce authentication."},{"heading":"18. Schema Documentation","content":"Use GraphQL introspection, Apollo Studio docs, and SDL comments."},{"heading":"19. Client-side Practices","content":"Use fragments, caching policies, codegen, and query batching on the client."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep types modular\n- Avoid over-fetching fields\n- Document with @deprecated\n- Use schema-first development"}],"related":["python-roadmap","unity-roadmap","expressjs-roadmap","heroku-roadmap","sanity-io-roadmap"]},{"slug":"rest-api-roadmap","title":"REST API Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master RESTful API design and development in 2025 covering architecture, best practices, security, documentation, testing, and scalability.","sections":[{"heading":"What is REST API?","content":"REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style for designing networked applications using HTTP methods and resource-oriented URLs."},{"heading":"Why REST?","content":"REST APIs are simple, scalable, widely supported, and language-agnostic, making them the standard for web services."},{"heading":"1. Core Principles","content":"Understand resources, statelessness, HTTP verbs (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH), and status codes (200, 201, 204, 400, 404, 500).","code":"GET /api/users → 200 OK\nPOST /api/users → 201 Created"},{"heading":"2. Designing Endpoints","content":"Use consistent naming (plural nouns), versioning (/v1/users), filtering, pagination, and proper nesting.","links":[{"text":"RESTful API Design Guide","href":"https://restfulapi.net/resource-naming/"}]},{"heading":"3. Request & Response Formats","content":"Use JSON, negotiate with Content-Type and Accept headers, include hypermedia (HATEOAS) when useful."},{"heading":"4. Authentication & Authorization","content":"Implement stateless methods like JWT, OAuth2 Bearer tokens, or API keys.","code":"Authorization: Bearer <token>"},{"heading":"5. Validation & Error Handling","content":"Validate payloads, return structured errors (code, message, details), and use appropriate HTTP statuses.","code":"{ \"error\": \"Invalid input\", \"details\": {\"email\": \"Invalid format\"} }"},{"heading":"6. Documentation & OpenAPI","content":"Use OpenAPI/Swagger to publish API specs and generate client/server code.","links":[{"text":"OpenAPI Specification","href":"https://swagger.io/specification/"}]},{"heading":"7. Versioning Strategy","content":"Use URL/versioning (`/v1/...`), header-based versioning, or content negotiation. Maintain backwards compatibility."},{"heading":"8. Rate Limiting & Throttling","content":"Protect endpoints using rate limits, quotas, and leaky bucket algorithms."},{"heading":"9. Caching","content":"Use HTTP caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control), CDN layers, and conditional GETs."},{"heading":"10. Security Best Practices","content":"Enforce TLS, use input sanitization, guard against injection, CSRF, XSS; apply CORS policies."},{"heading":"11. Testing & Mocking","content":"Use Postman/Newman, integration tests, contract tests (Pact), and mocking servers."},{"heading":"12. Monitoring & Logging","content":"Log requests/responses, monitor latency/errors, use tools like Prometheus, Grafana, ELK."},{"heading":"13. Performance & Scalability","content":"Implement pagination, shard DB, use connection pooling, async processing/worker queues."},{"heading":"14. Asynchronous Patterns","content":"Support webhooks, polling, or long-poll/streaming for async communication."},{"heading":"15. Client Generation & SDKs","content":"Generate client libraries in multiple languages using OpenAPI codegen."},{"heading":"16. Deployment Strategies","content":"Use containers (Docker), orchestrate with Kubernetes, deploy API gateways (Kong, AWS API Gateway)."},{"heading":"17. GraphQL & REST Coexistence","content":"When appropriate, adopt GraphQL or Hypermedia APIs for flexibility or complex querying."},{"heading":"18. Governance & API Lifecycle","content":"Document deprecation policy, maintain change logs, use API portals/management tools."},{"heading":"19. Documentation Portals & Developer Experience","content":"Use tools like Redoc, Stoplight, or ReadMe to publish interactive docs."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep APIs intuitive and consistent\n- Follow HAL or JSON:API\n- Provide proper versioning and error codes\n- Use TLS and secure tokens"}],"related":["java-roadmap","rust-roadmap","p5js-roadmap","redis-roadmap","elasticsearch-roadmap"]},{"slug":"web3-roadmap","title":"Web3 Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Web3 and blockchain development in 2025 with this roadmap covering core concepts, smart contracts, DApps, DeFi, and Ethereum ecosystem tools.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Web3?","content":"Web3 refers to decentralized web applications running on public blockchains with users retaining control of their data and digital assets."},{"heading":"Why Web3?","content":"Web3 enables trustless, censorship-resistant apps, financial inclusion via DeFi, and new ownership models via NFTs."},{"heading":"1. Blockchain Basics","content":"Understand blocks, transactions, consensus (PoW, PoS), wallets, addresses."},{"heading":"2. Ethereum & EVM","content":"Learn Ethereum architecture, accounts, gas, and smart contract execution."},{"heading":"3. Smart Contracts (Solidity)","content":"Write contracts in Solidity, following security patterns, and compile with `solc` or Hardhat/Truffle.","code":"pragma solidity ^0.8.0;\ncontract Hello { string public name;\n function setName(string calldata n) public { name = n; } }"},{"heading":"4. Development Frameworks","content":"Use Truffle, Hardhat, Foundry, and Brownie to compile, test, and deploy contracts.","links":[{"text":"Hardhat Docs","href":"https://hardhat.org/docs"}]},{"heading":"5. Testing & Security","content":"Write Solidity tests, use OpenZeppelin, run audits, use MythX/Slither/Certora."},{"heading":"6. ERC Standards (ERC-20/721/1155)","content":"Implement and understand token standards for fungible and non-fungible tokens."},{"heading":"7. Oracles & Off-chain Data","content":"Use Chainlink oracles, adapt to external data, and decentralize inputs."},{"heading":"8. DApp Frontends","content":"Build web frontends using web3.js, ethers.js, Wagmi, and MetaMask integration."},{"heading":"9. Wallets & Authentication","content":"Interact with MetaMask, WalletConnect, and handle user sessions via wallet signatures."},{"heading":"10. Layer-2 & Scaling","content":"Use Optimism, Arbitrum, and zk-rollups to reduce fees and increase throughput."},{"heading":"11. DeFi Primitives","content":"Learn AMMs, liquidity pools, lending protocols, yield farming."},{"heading":"12. Governance & DAOs","content":"Create on-chain governance, proposals, and tokens for decentralized orgs."},{"heading":"13. NFTs & Tokenization","content":"Mint NFTs, design metadata standards, integrate IPFS/Arweave storage."},{"heading":"14. Cross-chain & Bridges","content":"Use Axelar, Wormhole, or custom bridges for asset and data interoperability."},{"heading":"15. Backend Infrastructure","content":"Use services like TheGraph, Moralis, QuickNode, or run own nodes."},{"heading":"16. Security & Best Practices","content":"Defend against reentrancy, front-running; use multi-sig, audits, and time locks."},{"heading":"17. Tokenomics & Economics","content":"Design supply, incentives, governance models, and token distribution plans."},{"heading":"18. Deployment & Upgrade Patterns","content":"Use proxy patterns, upgradeability via OpenZeppelin and careful migrations."},{"heading":"19. Auditing & Compliance","content":"Conduct audits, use bug bounties, maintain transparency and regulatory alignment."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Favor modular contracts and libraries\n- Use gas-efficient patterns\n- Document interfaces and events\n- Keep keys secure and tokens audited"}],"related":["ubuntu-roadmap","springboot-roadmap","grafana-roadmap","kubernetes-roadmap","mocha-roadmap"]},{"slug":"solidity-roadmap","title":"Solidity Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Solidity in 2025 with this roadmap covering language fundamentals, smart contract design, testing, security, deployment, and advanced patterns.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Solidity?","content":"Solidity is a statically‑typed, contract‑oriented language designed for writing smart contracts that run on Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM)."},{"heading":"Why Solidity?","content":"It’s the dominant language for Ethereum smart contracts and compatible blockchains, with rich community support and tooling."},{"heading":"1. Environment Setup","content":"Install Node.js, npm, Solidity compiler (`solc`), and developer frameworks like Hardhat and Truffle.","links":[{"text":"Hardhat Documentation","href":"https://hardhat.org/docs"},{"text":"Truffle Suite Docs","href":"https://trufflesuite.com/docs/"}]},{"heading":"2. Basic Syntax","content":"Understand pragma, types, variables, functions, visibility, and modifiers.","code":"pragma solidity ^0.8.0;\ncontract Counter {\n  uint public count;\n  function increment() public { count += 1; }\n}"},{"heading":"3. Control Structures & Error Handling","content":"Use if/else, for/while, `require`, `assert`, and `revert`.","code":"function withdraw(uint amount) public {\n  require(msg.sender == owner, \"Not owner\");\n  (bool ok,) = msg.sender.call{ value: amount }(\"\");\n  require(ok, \"Transfer failed\");\n}"},{"heading":"4. Events & Logging","content":"Emit events for indexing and off-chain listening.","code":"event Deposited(address indexed user, uint amount);\nfunction deposit() payable public {\n  emit Deposited(msg.sender, msg.value);\n}"},{"heading":"5. Data Structures","content":"Use mappings, arrays, structs, and dynamic memory vs storage.","code":"struct User { uint id; string name; }\nmapping(address => User) public users;"},{"heading":"6. Contract Inheritance & Interfaces","content":"Use `is`, override, abstract contracts, and interface definitions.","code":"interface IERC20 { function totalSupply() external view returns (uint); }\ncontract MyToken is IERC20 { ... }"},{"heading":"7. Libraries & Reuse","content":"Write reusable libraries and use `using for` syntax.","code":"library SafeMath { function add(uint a, uint b) internal pure returns (uint) { return a + b; } }\nusing SafeMath for uint;"},{"heading":"8. Testing","content":"Write tests in JavaScript, TypeScript, or Solidity using Hardhat or Truffle.","code":"describe(\"Counter\", () => { it(\"increments\", async () => { ... }); });"},{"heading":"9. Security Best Practices","content":"Avoid reentrancy, do checks-effects-interactions, handle overflows, use OpenZeppelin's libraries.","links":[{"text":"OpenZeppelin Contracts","href":"https://docs.openzeppelin.com/contracts"}]},{"heading":"10. Upgradeable Contracts","content":"Implement proxies or use OpenZeppelin upgradable plugin.","code":"// use ERC1967Proxy or TransparentUpgradeableProxy"},{"heading":"11. Gas Optimization","content":"Minimize storage writes, pack variables, avoid loops, use `calldata`.","code":"uint8 a; uint8 b; // packed into single slot"},{"heading":"12. Oracles & Off‑Chain Data","content":"Integrate Chainlink oracles for external data feeds."},{"heading":"13. Token Standards","content":"Implement ERC‑20/ERC‑721/ERC‑1155 standards correctly."},{"heading":"14. Access Control","content":"Use roles like `Ownable`, multi‑sig, `AccessControl` via OpenZeppelin."},{"heading":"15. Deployment","content":"Deploy using Hardhat, Truffle or scripts to networks like Mainnet, Arbitrum, Polygon, etc."},{"heading":"16. Verification & Explorer Integration","content":"Verify contracts on Etherscan/Polygonscan post-deployment."},{"heading":"17. Documentation & NatSpec","content":"Write NatSpec comments (`@notice`, `@dev`) for user and developer documentation."},{"heading":"18. Auditing & Bug Bounties","content":"Use tools like MythX, Slither, Echidna; run audit programs and bounty campaigns."},{"heading":"19. Ecosystem Integration","content":"Integrate with DeFi protocols, wallets (MetaMask), DEXes, and tooling."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Write modular, testable code\n- Use standardized libraries\n- Avoid block.timestamp for critical logic\n- Keep contracts minimal in size"}],"related":["langchain-roadmap","prometheus-roadmap","unreal-engine-roadmap","java-roadmap","blender-roadmap"]},{"slug":"blockchain-roadmap","title":"Blockchain Roadmap: A Comprehensive Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master blockchain development in 2025—covering fundamentals, consensus, smart contracts, scaling, security, DeFi, and ecosystem tools.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Blockchain?","content":"A blockchain is a distributed ledger of transactions secured by cryptography and consensus mechanisms."},{"heading":"Why Blockchain?","content":"Provides decentralization, immutability, transparency, and enables new models like DeFi, NFTs, DAOs."},{"heading":"1. Distributed Ledger Basics","content":"Learn blocks, transactions, hash chains, Merkle trees."},{"heading":"2. Consensus Algorithms","content":"Understand PoW (Bitcoin), PoS (Ethereum), DPoS, BFT variants like Tendermint."},{"heading":"3. Cryptography Fundamentals","content":"Use hashing (SHA‑256), public/private keys, digital signatures (ECDSA).","code":"// publicKey = secp256k1.generate();"},{"heading":"4. Nodes & Network","content":"Run full vs light nodes; understand P2P networking protocols."},{"heading":"5. Smart Contracts & Virtual Machines","content":"Write contracts in Solidity, WASM (e.g. Substrate), or chain‑specific languages."},{"heading":"6. Tokens & Standards","content":"Implement ERC-20, ERC-721, ERC-1155, fungible and non-fungible token standards."},{"heading":"7. DApp Architecture","content":"Combine frontend (React), contracts (Solidity), backend (TheGraph) in DApps."},{"heading":"8. Transactions & Fees","content":"Gas models, dynamic fees (EIP-1559), mempool behavior."},{"heading":"9. Wallets & Key Management","content":"Use MetaMask, hardware wallets, custodial vs non‑custodial key storage."},{"heading":"10. Interoperability & Bridges","content":"Cross-chain messaging with Cosmos IBC, bridges like Wormhole."},{"heading":"11. Layer 1 vs Layer 2","content":"Distinguish base chains and scaling layers (optimistic, zk‑rollups)."},{"heading":"12. Oracles & Data Feeds","content":"Fetch real-world data via Chainlink, Band Protocol."},{"heading":"13. DeFi Primitives","content":"Understand AMMs, lending, liquidity pools, yield farming."},{"heading":"14. Governance & DAOs","content":"Implement on-chain governance via tokens and proposals."},{"heading":"15. Privacy & ZK Tech","content":"Explore zero-knowledge proofs, zk-SNARKs, privacy networks like ZCash."},{"heading":"16. Security & Attacks","content":"Learn reentrancy, oracle manipulation, flash loan attacks, and mitigation."},{"heading":"17. Scaling & Performance","content":"RPC scaling, state channels, sharding, archiving."},{"heading":"18. Regulation & Compliance","content":"Study KYC/AML, token securities, GDPR, reporting."},{"heading":"19. Ecosystem Tooling","content":"Use Full nodes, Infura, Alchemy, TheGraph, Ethers.js/Web3.js, Hardhat plugins."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Use standardized frameworks\n- Perform audits and tests\n- Use least-privilege patterns\n- Stay updated on protocol changes"}],"related":["hardhat-roadmap","recoil-roadmap","openai-api-roadmap","rails-roadmap","new-relic-roadmap"]},{"slug":"metamask-roadmap","title":"MetaMask Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master MetaMask in 2025 with this roadmap covering wallet setup, integration with DApps, security, developer tools, and best practices.","sections":[{"heading":"What is MetaMask?","content":"MetaMask is a browser and mobile Ethereum wallet that enables users to manage digital assets, interact with DApps, and sign blockchain transactions."},{"heading":"Why MetaMask?","content":"It’s the most widely used Web3 wallet with strong ecosystem support, wallet connect, and deep integration in Ethereum-based applications."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install MetaMask extension or mobile app, create/import wallet with seed phrase, and set up password."},{"heading":"2. Addresses & Accounts","content":"Understand hierarchical deterministic (HD) wallets, multiple accounts, and custom networks."},{"heading":"3. Network Management","content":"Switch between Ethereum mainnet, testnets, and custom RPC networks like Binance Smart Chain."},{"heading":"4. Sending & Receiving ETH/Tokens","content":"Transfer assets, view token balances, and add custom tokens via contract address."},{"heading":"5. Integration with DApps","content":"Use `window.ethereum`, detect provider, request accounts, call `eth_sendTransaction`."},{"heading":"6. Signing & Security","content":"Manage transaction confirmation, signature prompts, confirmation dialogs, and hardware wallet support."},{"heading":"7. Permissions & Privacy","content":"Approve DApp permissions, disconnect sites, and limit account exposure."},{"heading":"8. Token Swaps & DeFi Use","content":"Use built-in swap UI, interact with DeFi protocols directly from the wallet."},{"heading":"9. WalletConnect & Alternatives","content":"Use WalletConnect to connect mobile or alternative Web3 wallets."},{"heading":"10. Smart Contract Interactions","content":"Call smart contract methods, encode ABI, handle gas fees."},{"heading":"11. Developer Tools & Debugging","content":"Use MetaMask `Provider API`, inspect RPC logs, debug using remix.ethereum.org."},{"heading":"12. Gas Management","content":"Use advanced gas controls, limit/gas price, and EIP‑1559 fee model."},{"heading":"13. Custom RPC & Chain Configuration","content":"Manually add custom networks, custom block explorers, and chain IDs."},{"heading":"14. Tokens & NFTs Management","content":"Display ERC‑20 tokens and ERC‑721/1155 NFTs, use IPFS-based metadata."},{"heading":"15. Mobile Features","content":"Use QR-code scanning, wallet connect, biometric unlock, and in-app browsing."},{"heading":"16. Security Best Practices","content":"Avoid phishing, seed safety, use hardware wallets and regular backups."},{"heading":"17. Developer Integrations","content":"Use MetaMask Snaps, inject custom APIs into wallet, and extend functionality."},{"heading":"18. Testing DApps with MetaMask","content":"Use local networks (Ganache, Hardhat), test signing and transactions in test environments."},{"heading":"19. Advanced Features","content":"Take part in governance, view on‑chain assets, integrate wallet dapps SDKs."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Educate users about phishing\n- Limit RPC permissions\n- Use secure communication channels\n- Properly handle errors and rejections"}],"related":["flask-roadmap","nextauthjs-roadmap","supabase-roadmap","android-roadmap","php-roadmap"]},{"slug":"truffle-roadmap","title":"Truffle Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Truffle in 2025 with this roadmap covering environment setup, migrations, testing, Ganache, web3 integration, and advanced workflows.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Truffle?","content":"Truffle is a development framework for Ethereum smart contracts, offering testing, deployment, and asset pipeline tooling."},{"heading":"Why Truffle?","content":"It simplifies contract compilation, network deployment, scriptable migrations, and automated testing—ideal for full-stack blockchain development."},{"heading":"1. Install & Setup","content":"Install via npm: `npm install -g truffle`, initialize projects with `truffle init`."},{"heading":"2. Project Structure","content":"Understand Truffle’s default structure: contracts/, migrations/, test/, truffle-config.js."},{"heading":"3. Compile Contracts","content":"Use `truffle compile` to compile Solidity logic for use."},{"heading":"4. Migrations","content":"Write and run migrations using JS migration scripts with `deployer.deploy()`."},{"heading":"5. Ganache Local Blockchain","content":"Use Ganache CLI or GUI to spin up a personal Ethereum blockchain."},{"heading":"6. Testing Contracts","content":"Write tests in JavaScript or Solidity using Mocha/Chai."},{"heading":"7. Interacting via Console","content":"Use `truffle console` to interact with deployed contracts on a network."},{"heading":"8. Network Configuration","content":"Setup truffle-config.js for development, test, and production networks."},{"heading":"9. Web3 & Front-End Integration","content":"Use Web3.js or ethers.js to call Truffle-deployed contracts from frontend apps."},{"heading":"10. Advanced Migrations","content":"Deploy libraries, upgradeable contracts, and multi-step deployment flows."},{"heading":"11. Debugging & Error Handling","content":"Use `truffle debug`, inspect stack traces, and fix revert errors."},{"heading":"12. Plugins Ecosystem","content":"Use Truffle Boxes (templates) and plugins like `truffle-plugin-verify`."},{"heading":"13. Deployment to Testnets & Mainnet","content":"Use Infura/Alchemy provider configs and secure private keys for deployment."},{"heading":"14. Front-End Asset Pipeline","content":"Use Truffle’s React/Vue box setup with migrations for dApp UIs."},{"heading":"15. Contract Verification","content":"Integrate Etherscan verification via `truffle-plugin-verify`."},{"heading":"16. HD Wallet & Providers","content":"Use HDWalletProvider or similar to sign transactions during migration."},{"heading":"17. Scriptable Tasks","content":"Write custom Truffle scripts for data seeding or migration tasks."},{"heading":"18. CI/CD Integration","content":"Integrate Truffle tests and migrations in CI pipelines (GitHub Actions)."},{"heading":"19. Best Practices","content":"- Keep migration IDs ordered\n- Use network-specific configs\n- Write extensive tests\n- Avoid hardcoded addresses in code"},{"heading":"20. Community & Support","content":"Engage in Truffle community, use Mix workshops, forums, and GitHub issues."}],"related":["graphql-roadmap","rest-api-roadmap","java-roadmap","flask-roadmap","typescript-roadmap"]},{"slug":"hardhat-roadmap","title":"Hardhat Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Hardhat in 2025 with this roadmap covering environment setup, scripting, testing, deployment, plugins, and advanced workflows.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Hardhat?","content":"Hardhat is a flexible Ethereum development environment for compiling, testing, debugging, and deploying smart contracts."},{"heading":"Why Hardhat?","content":"It offers fast compilation, extensive plugin ecosystem, powerful debugging, and seamless integration with Solidity and TypeScript."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install via npm: `npm install --save-dev hardhat`, then run `npx hardhat` to initialize project."},{"heading":"2. Project Structure","content":"Understanding the layout: contracts/, scripts/, test/, hardhat.config.js."},{"heading":"3. Compiler Configuration","content":"Set multiple compiler versions and optimization settings.","code":"module.exports = { solidity: { compilers: [{ version: '0.8.18', settings: { optimizer: { enabled: true, runs: 200 } } }] } };"},{"heading":"4. Hardhat Network","content":"Use built-in local Ethereum network with forking and custom accounts."},{"heading":"5. Scripting & Tasks","content":"Write scripts for deployments or custom tasks.","code":"task('accounts', 'Prints list of accounts', async (_, hre) => { const accounts = await hre.ethers.getSigners(); accounts.forEach(a => console.log(a.address)); });"},{"heading":"6. Debugging & Console","content":"Use `console.log` in Solidity and `npx hardhat node --no-deploy`."},{"heading":"7. Testing with Mocha/Chai","content":"Write unit tests using `hardhat-ethers` and assertions with Chai.","code":"describe('MyContract', () => { it('should do X', async () => { const contract = await ethers.deployContract('MyContract'); expect(await contract.value()).to.equal(0); }); });"},{"heading":"8. Contract Deployment","content":"Use scripts and network configuration for multiple environments."},{"heading":"9. Plugins Ecosystem","content":"Use plugins like `hardhat-deploy`, `hardhat-etherscan`, `hardhat-gas-reporter`."},{"heading":"10. Ethereum Mainnet Forking","content":"Test contracts against real on-chain data for forking accuracy."},{"heading":"11. TypeScript Integration","content":"Use TypeChain and typings for strong developer experience."},{"heading":"12. Etherscan Verification","content":"Automate contract verification using `hardhat-etherscan` plugin."},{"heading":"13. Gas Usage Reporting","content":"Track gas usage and optimize contracts using `hardhat-gas-reporter`."},{"heading":"14. Security Tools","content":"Integrate linters and reachability tools; support Slither."},{"heading":"15. Coverage Analysis","content":"Generate test coverage reports using `solidity-coverage`."},{"heading":"16. Upgradeable Contract Support","content":"Use OpenZeppelin upgrades plugin for proxies."},{"heading":"17. Multi-Network Deployment","content":"Configure for localhost, testnets, and mainnet."},{"heading":"18. CI/CD Integration","content":"Run tests, coverage, and verifications in GitHub Actions or GitLab CI."},{"heading":"19. Documentation & Community","content":"Use Hardhat docs, Discord, and community tutorials."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep tasks modular\n- Use type-safe configs\n- Pin plugin versions\n- Enforce test coverage thresholds"}],"related":["langchain-roadmap","zustand-roadmap","cypress-roadmap","chartjs-roadmap","firebase-roadmap"]},{"slug":"jest-roadmap","title":"Jest Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Jest testing in 2025 with this roadmap covering setup, test types, mocks, coverage, performance, and advanced patterns.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Jest?","content":"Jest is a zero-config JavaScript testing framework by Facebook for unit, integration, and snapshot testing."},{"heading":"Why Jest?","content":"It offers fast tests, easy mocking, code coverage, snapshot testing, and works out of the box with React and Node.js."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Config","content":"Install `jest --save-dev`, add `jest` script in package.json, configure `jest.config.js` if needed."},{"heading":"2. Basic Unit Tests","content":"Write simple tests with `test()` and `expect()`.","code":"test('adds 1 + 2 to equal 3', () => { expect(1 + 2).toBe(3); });"},{"heading":"3. Testing React Components","content":"Use `@testing-library/react` for rendering and assertions.","code":"import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react'; test('renders button', () => { render(<MyButton />); expect(screen.getByText('Click')).toBeInTheDocument(); });"},{"heading":"4. Mocking (functions/modules)","content":"Use `jest.fn()` and `jest.mock()` to isolate dependencies."},{"heading":"5. Asynchronous Tests","content":"Use `async/await`, `.resolves`, `.rejects`, and `done()` for async code."},{"heading":"6. Snapshot Testing","content":"Store component output snapshot with `toMatchSnapshot()`."},{"heading":"7. Code Coverage","content":"Generate coverage reports with `--coverage` flag and thresholds configuration."},{"heading":"8. Setup & Teardown Hooks","content":"Use `beforeAll`, `afterEach`, etc., for test preparation and cleanup."},{"heading":"9. Parameterized Tests","content":"Use `test.each()` for table-driven scenarios."},{"heading":"10. Custom Matchers","content":"Extend Jest with custom matchers via `expect.extend()`."},{"heading":"11. Integration Testing","content":"Test full modules combining multiple functions or APIs."},{"heading":"12. Testing DOM & Browser APIs","content":"Configure `jsdom`; mock `window` and `localStorage`."},{"heading":"13. Performance Optimization","content":"Use `--runInBand`, `--maxWorkers`, and watch mode during development."},{"heading":"14. Coverage Threshold Enforcement","content":"Fail CI if coverage drops below defined percentages."},{"heading":"15. Watch Mode & Snapshots","content":"Use `jest --watch` to rerun tests on changes."},{"heading":"16. Debugging Tests","content":"Use `--verbose`, `--detectLeaks`, and integrate with VSCode debugger."},{"heading":"17. Testing API Endpoints","content":"Use `supertest` to test Express.js or Koa APIs."},{"heading":"18. Typescript Integration","content":"Use `ts-jest` for type-safe testing."},{"heading":"19. CI/CD Integration","content":"Run Jest in CI, collect coverage, and report badges."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep tests fast and isolated\n- Mock external services\n- Write assertions with intent\n- Clean up resources after tests"}],"related":["webrtc-roadmap","csharp-roadmap","ios-roadmap","react-roadmap","github-roadmap"]},{"slug":"mocha-roadmap","title":"Mocha Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Mocha in 2025 with this comprehensive guide covering setup, assertions, hooks, async testing, BDD/TDD styles, and integrations.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Mocha?","content":"Mocha is a feature-rich JavaScript test framework running on Node.js and in the browser, making asynchronous testing simple and flexible."},{"heading":"Why Mocha?","content":"Mocha supports both BDD and TDD, has powerful hooks, detailed error reporting, and integrates well with assertion libraries like Chai."},{"heading":"1. Installing Mocha","content":"Install Mocha locally using npm: `npm install --save-dev mocha`."},{"heading":"2. Writing Your First Test","content":"Create a `test/` folder, add test files, and run `npx mocha`.","code":"const assert = require('assert');\ndescribe('Array', function () {\n  it('should return -1 when not found', function () {\n    assert.strictEqual([1, 2, 3].indexOf(4), -1);\n  });\n});"},{"heading":"3. Using Chai for Assertions","content":"Combine Mocha with Chai: `npm install chai`.","code":"const { expect } = require('chai');\nexpect([1, 2, 3].indexOf(4)).to.equal(-1);"},{"heading":"4. BDD vs TDD Style","content":"Use `describe/it` for BDD or `suite/test` for TDD. Choose your preferred style."},{"heading":"5. Synchronous vs Asynchronous Tests","content":"Support for callbacks, Promises, and async/await.","code":"it('supports async/await', async function () {\n  const result = await someAsyncFunc();\n  expect(result).to.be.true;\n});"},{"heading":"6. Setup and Teardown with Hooks","content":"Use `before`, `beforeEach`, `after`, `afterEach` to control test lifecycle."},{"heading":"7. Test Organization","content":"Use nested `describe()` blocks to structure large test suites."},{"heading":"8. Working with Test Fixtures","content":"Use Mocha hooks to setup test fixtures or mocks before tests run."},{"heading":"9. Running Tests","content":"Run with CLI: `npx mocha`, use `--recursive`, `--reporter`, etc."},{"heading":"10. Custom Reporters","content":"Use built-in or 3rd-party reporters like `mochawesome`.","links":[{"text":"Mochawesome Reporter","href":"https://github.com/adamgruber/mochawesome"}]},{"heading":"11. Code Coverage with nyc","content":"Use `nyc` (Istanbul): `npx nyc mocha` for code coverage.","links":[{"text":"nyc Docs","href":"https://github.com/istanbuljs/nyc"}]},{"heading":"12. Watch Mode","content":"Use `mocha --watch` to rerun tests on file changes."},{"heading":"13. CI/CD Integration","content":"Use Mocha in GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins etc."},{"heading":"14. Testing HTTP APIs","content":"Use `supertest` or `chai-http` with Mocha.","code":"chai.request(server).get('/api/users').end((err, res) => {\n  expect(res).to.have.status(200);\n});"},{"heading":"15. TypeScript with Mocha","content":"Use `ts-node` to run Mocha tests written in TypeScript.","code":"npx mocha -r ts-node/register tests/**/*.test.ts"},{"heading":"16. Best Practices","content":"Use async/await, clean up in `afterEach`, group tests logically, and avoid shared state."}],"related":["react-roadmap","prometheus-roadmap","github-roadmap","langchain-roadmap","huggingface-roadmap"]},{"slug":"cypress-roadmap","title":"Cypress Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Cypress in 2025 with this roadmap covering end-to-end testing, commands, intercepts, components, CI integration, and advanced automation techniques.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Cypress?","content":"Cypress is a modern JavaScript-based end-to-end testing framework for web applications. It runs directly in the browser, offering real-time debugging and a developer-friendly interface."},{"heading":"Why Cypress?","content":"Cypress offers fast execution, powerful UI, time travel debugging, automatic waits, network stubbing, and first-class support for modern JavaScript apps."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install via npm: `npm install cypress --save-dev`, then run `npx cypress open`."},{"heading":"2. Folder Structure","content":"Tests are inside `cypress/e2e`, commands in `cypress/support/commands.js`."},{"heading":"3. Writing Your First Test","content":"Use `cy.visit()`, `cy.get()`, `cy.click()` to simulate user interactions.","code":"describe('Login Flow', () => {\n  it('logs in successfully', () => {\n    cy.visit('/login');\n    cy.get('#username').type('user');\n    cy.get('#password').type('pass');\n    cy.get('form').submit();\n    cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');\n  });\n});"},{"heading":"4. Assertions and Queries","content":"Use `.should()`, `.contains()`, `.eq()` for testing DOM elements."},{"heading":"5. Custom Commands","content":"Define reusable actions in `commands.js`.","code":"Cypress.Commands.add('login', (email, pw) => {\n  cy.get('#email').type(email);\n  cy.get('#password').type(pw);\n  cy.get('form').submit();\n});"},{"heading":"6. Network Requests","content":"Use `cy.intercept()` to stub or spy on XHR/fetch calls.","code":"cy.intercept('GET', '/api/data', { fixture: 'data.json' });"},{"heading":"7. Fixtures and Data Mocking","content":"Mock server data using static JSON in `cypress/fixtures` folder."},{"heading":"8. Component Testing","content":"Use `@cypress/react` to test React/Vue components in isolation.","links":[{"text":"Component Testing Docs","href":"https://docs.cypress.io/guides/component-testing/introduction"}]},{"heading":"9. Running Headless","content":"Use `npx cypress run --browser chrome --headless` for CI environments."},{"heading":"10. Screenshots and Videos","content":"Automatically capture screenshots on failure and videos during test runs."},{"heading":"11. Parallelization & CI","content":"Run tests in parallel using Cypress Dashboard with GitHub Actions, CircleCI, GitLab CI."},{"heading":"12. Code Coverage","content":"Integrate `@cypress/code-coverage` plugin to measure test coverage."},{"heading":"13. Environment Variables","content":"Use `cypress.env.json` or CLI env vars: `CYPRESS_API_URL=http://...`"},{"heading":"14. Cypress Dashboard","content":"Record test runs, parallelization, and insights using the cloud dashboard.","links":[{"text":"Cypress Dashboard","href":"https://www.cypress.io/dashboard/"}]},{"heading":"15. Best Practices","content":"Use `data-cy` selectors, avoid `cy.wait()`, separate e2e/component tests, clean up before assertions."}],"related":["javascript-roadmap","blockchain-roadmap","ios-roadmap","new-relic-roadmap","typescript-roadmap"]},{"slug":"playwright-roadmap","title":"Playwright Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Playwright in 2025 with this roadmap covering setup, browser automation, testing strategies, CI integrations, performance, and advanced workflows.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Playwright?","content":"Playwright is a modern end-to-end testing framework from Microsoft that allows cross-browser automation for Chromium, Firefox, and WebKit with a single API."},{"heading":"Why Playwright?","content":"It offers fast parallel execution, full browser control, auto-waiting, powerful debugging tools, and support for multiple languages."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install via npm or pip. Use `npm i -D @playwright/test` and `npx playwright install` to set up browsers."},{"heading":"2. Basic Test Structure","content":"Use `test.describe`, `test`, and `expect` for structuring your test files.","code":"import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';\ntest('homepage has title', async ({ page }) => {\n  await page.goto('https://example.com');\n  await expect(page).toHaveTitle(/Example/);\n});"},{"heading":"3. Selectors & Locators","content":"Use `page.locator()` with CSS, text, role, and XPath selectors for robust targeting."},{"heading":"4. Auto-Waiting & Actions","content":"Playwright automatically waits for elements to appear before performing actions."},{"heading":"5. Handling Frames & Popups","content":"Use `page.frame()` and `page.waitForEvent('popup')` to interact across contexts."},{"heading":"6. Network Interception","content":"Use `page.route()` or `page.waitForRequest()` to stub or inspect network calls."},{"heading":"7. Debugging & Tracing","content":"Use `PWDEBUG=1`, inspector videos, screenshots on failure, and full trace recording."},{"heading":"8. Parameterized & Data-Driven Tests","content":"Use `test.describe.parallel` and `test.each()` for data-driven scenarios."},{"heading":"9. Cross-Browser Testing","content":"Run tests against Chromium, WebKit, and Firefox using config `projects` settings."},{"heading":"10. CI/CD Integration","content":"Integrate with GitHub Actions, GitLab, Jenkins; upload traces and reports."},{"heading":"11. Performance Testing","content":"Measure performance with tracing, screenshot timing, and Console events."},{"heading":"12. Accessibility Testing","content":"Use `page.accessibility.snapshot()` to evaluate accessible tree."},{"heading":"13. Mobile Web & Emulation","content":"Use built-in device descriptors to emulate mobile viewports."},{"heading":"14. Visual Regression Testing","content":"Compare screenshots pixel-by-pixel or use `toHaveScreenshot()`."},{"heading":"15. Test Fixtures & Hooks","content":"Use fixtures (`test.use`) and hooks (`beforeAll`, `afterEach`) for setup."},{"heading":"16. Test Reporting","content":"Generate HTML reports or send JSON to external dashboard systems."},{"heading":"17. Code Coverage & Linting","content":"Integrate with TypeScript, ESLint, and collect coverage using OpenTelemetry."},{"heading":"18. Complex Workflows","content":"Handle file uploads/downloads, dialogs, geolocation, and permissions."},{"heading":"19. Plugin Ecosystem","content":"Use plugin ecosystem for onboarding, video playback, and Jenkins integration."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep tests independent\n- Use explicit timeouts only when needed\n- Clean up after each test\n- Avoid hard-coding selectors"}],"related":["vue-roadmap","unreal-engine-roadmap","terraform-roadmap","kubernetes-roadmap","algolia-roadmap"]},{"slug":"redux-roadmap","title":"Redux Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Redux in 2025 with this roadmap covering core concepts, middleware, TypeScript support, advanced patterns, and integration with modern tooling.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Redux?","content":"Redux is a predictable state container for JavaScript apps, often used with React, Angular, Vue, or even vanilla JS."},{"heading":"Why Redux?","content":"It centralizes application state, makes debugging easier with tools like Redux DevTools, supports time-travel debugging, and enforces immutability."},{"heading":"1. Core Concepts","content":"Learn state, actions, reducers, and store initialization."},{"heading":"2. Creating a Store","content":"Use `configureStore` from Redux Toolkit or `createStore` for vanilla Redux.","code":"import { configureStore } from '@reduxjs/toolkit';\nconst store = configureStore({ reducer: rootReducer });"},{"heading":"3. Actions & Reducers","content":"Define action creators, action types, and pure reducers using switch cases or `createSlice()`."},{"heading":"4. Redux Toolkit","content":"Use Toolkit `createSlice`, `createAsyncThunk`, and Immer for immutable updates.","code":"const todosSlice = createSlice({ name: 'todos', initialState: [], reducers: { add: (state, action) => { state.push(action.payload); } } });"},{"heading":"5. Dispatching Actions","content":"Use `store.dispatch(action)` or `useDispatch()` in React components."},{"heading":"6. Selectors & Memoization","content":"Use `useSelector`, `createSelector()` from Reselect for efficient derived data."},{"heading":"7. Middleware","content":"Implement side effects with `redux-thunk`, `redux-saga`, or `redux-observable`."},{"heading":"8. Async Logic","content":"Use `createAsyncThunk` for async actions and handle pending/fulfilled/rejected states."},{"heading":"9. TypeScript Integration","content":"Use typed stores, actions, selectors with `PayloadAction`, `RootState`, and `AppDispatch`."},{"heading":"10. DevTools & Debugging","content":"Set up Redux DevTools and use time-travel debugging features."},{"heading":"11. Normalizing State","content":"Use `createEntityAdapter` to organize relational data efficiently."},{"heading":"12. Testing Redux Logic","content":"Write unit tests for reducers, thunks, and selectors using Jest."},{"heading":"13. React-Redux Hooks","content":"Use `useDispatch`, `useSelector`, `Provider`, `useStore`, and `batch()`."},{"heading":"14. Advanced Patterns","content":"Implement rehydration, optimistic updates, and undo/redo enhancements."},{"heading":"15. Performance Optimization","content":"Avoid unnecessary renders, memoize selectors, use `batch()`, and split reducers."},{"heading":"16. Code Splitting & Lazy Loading","content":"Load slices dynamically with `injectReducer()` or toolkit `configureStore` builder API."},{"heading":"17. Ecosystem Integrations","content":"Use with React, Angular, Vue and integrate with RTK Query, Reselect."},{"heading":"18. Server-side Rendering","content":"Use Redux with Next.js and Angular Universal for hydration support."},{"heading":"19. Best Practices","content":"- Use Redux Toolkit\n- Keep state minimal\n- Avoid state mutations\n- Document shape via TypeScript"}],"related":["kubernetes-roadmap","jest-roadmap","mongodb-roadmap","java-roadmap","vercel-roadmap"]},{"slug":"recoil-roadmap","title":"Recoil Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Recoil in 2025 with this roadmap covering its core concepts, state management patterns, performance optimization, and advanced features.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Recoil?","content":"Recoil is a state management library for React that enables shared state with atoms and selectors, offering minimal boilerplate and fine-grained performance."},{"heading":"Why Recoil?","content":"Recoil supports React's concurrent mode, split state across components, derive data automatically, and provide performant re-renders."},{"heading":"1. Getting Started","content":"Install using `npm install recoil`, wrap your app in `<RecoilRoot>`."},{"heading":"2. Atoms","content":"Create and use atoms for shared state.","code":"const textState = atom({ key: 'textState', default: '' });"},{"heading":"3. Selectors","content":"Define derived or asynchronous state using selectors.","code":"const charCountState = selector({ key: 'charCountState', get: ({get}) => get(textState).length });"},{"heading":"4. Component Usage","content":"Use `useRecoilState`, `useRecoilValue`, `useSetRecoilState` in functional components.","code":"const [text, setText] = useRecoilState(textState);"},{"heading":"5. Derived and Async State","content":"Use selectors to fetch data asynchronously.","code":"const asyncData = selector({ key: 'async', get: async () => fetch(...).then(r => r.json()) });"},{"heading":"6. Atom Effects","content":"Use atom effects for persistence or syncing with localStorage.","code":"effects_UNSTABLE: [ ({onSet}) => { onSet(newVal => localStorage.setItem('key', newVal)); } ]"},{"heading":"7. Atom Families","content":"Create parameterized atoms for dynamic keys.","code":"const todoAtom = atomFamily({ key: 'todo', default: id => defaultTodo });"},{"heading":"8. Performance Optimization","content":"Avoid large atoms; split state; batch updates with `useRecoilTransactionObserver`; update single atoms."},{"heading":"9. Recoil DevTools","content":"Use Recoil DevTools for time-travel and atom inspection."},{"heading":"10. Suspense Integration","content":"Combine async selectors and React Suspense fallbacks."},{"heading":"11. TypeScript Integration","content":"Define atom and selector types using generics.","code":"const numState = atom<number>({ key: 'numState', default: 0 });"},{"heading":"12. Multitenancy and Parallel Roots","content":"Use multiple `<RecoilRoot>` components with separate states."},{"heading":"13. Testing Recoil State","content":"Use `RecoilRoot` in test wrappers; unit test selector logic and atom updates."},{"heading":"14. Interoperability","content":"Combine with Redux, Context API, or Zustand through wrapper components."},{"heading":"15. Best Practices","content":"- Use small focused atoms\n- Avoid deeply nested selectors\n- Use families for dynamic lists\n- Cache async selectors"}],"related":["firebase-roadmap","solidity-roadmap","zustand-roadmap","bitbucket-roadmap","postgresql-roadmap"]},{"slug":"zustand-roadmap","title":"Zustand Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Zustand in 2025 with this roadmap covering setup, store configuration, middleware, TypeScript integration, and advanced store patterns.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Zustand?","content":"Zustand is a small, fast, and scalable state-management solution for React using hooks and context under the hood."},{"heading":"Why Zustand?","content":"Zustand has minimal boilerplate, no providers needed, and supports selectors, middleware, and pinning state to localStorage."},{"heading":"1. Getting Started","content":"Install via `npm install zustand` and create a store with `create()`."},{"heading":"2. Basic Store","content":"Define store with state and actions.","code":"const useStore = create(set => ({ count: 0, inc: () => set(s => ({ count: s.count + 1 })) }));"},{"heading":"3. Selectors & Shallow Comparison","content":"Use selectors to subscribe to only parts of the store.","code":"const count = useStore(s => s.count);"},{"heading":"4. Middleware: Logger, Persist","content":"Add middleware for logging and persistence.","code":"const useStore = create(devtools(persist(set => ({ ... }))))"},{"heading":"5. Async Actions","content":"Use async/await or `set()` callback for state updates.","code":"const fetcher = async () => { set({ loading: true }); const res = await fetch(...); set({ data: res.json(), loading: false }); }"},{"heading":"6. Splitting Stores","content":"Create multiple stores for isolation and better performance."},{"heading":"7. TypeScript Support","content":"Define store types using generics.","code":"interface State { count: number; inc: () => void; } const useStore = create<State>(set => ...);"},{"heading":"8. React Native & Middleware","content":"Use in React Native with middleware like `redux-persist` or `async-storage`."},{"heading":"9. Testing Zustand Stores","content":"Use `act()` in tests to reset or set store values."},{"heading":"10. SSR Support","content":"Use `createStore` manually, hydrate initial server state into client."},{"heading":"11. DevTools Integration","content":"Use `redux-devtools-extension` middleware and inspect state."},{"heading":"12. Derived State","content":"Use selectors with computed values for derived states."},{"heading":"13. Middleware Chain","content":"Combine logging, persistence, router sync using sequential middleware."},{"heading":"14. With React Context","content":"Share one store across modules without prop drilling using context/provider."},{"heading":"15. State Reset & Partial Updates","content":"Use `set({ ...initial });` to reset or partially modify store."},{"heading":"16. Optimizing Performance","content":"Use selectors, shallow, and split stores to avoid unnecessary renders."},{"heading":"17. Using Immer","content":"Integrate `immer` for mutative update style within actions."},{"heading":"18. Async Hooks Integration","content":"Combine Zustand with React Query or SWR for server-managed cache."},{"heading":"19. Best Practices","content":"- Keep stores small\n- Use middleware for needs\n- Always select minimal state\n- Write simple, testable actions"}],"related":["postgresql-roadmap","vue-roadmap","cpp-roadmap","firebase-roadmap","ios-roadmap"]},{"slug":"threejs-roadmap","title":"Three.js Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Three.js in 2025 with this roadmap covering scene setup, geometry, materials, lighting, animation, performance, and advanced rendering.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Three.js?","content":"Three.js is a popular JavaScript 3D library that simplifies WebGL, enabling developers to create interactive 3D graphics in the browser."},{"heading":"Why Three.js?","content":"It abstracts low-level WebGL details while offering full control, supports animations, shaders, post-processing, VR/AR, and enjoys a vibrant ecosystem."},{"heading":"1. Setup & Environment","content":"Install via npm (`npm install three`), or import via CDN; set up a basic HTML/Canvas environment.","code":"import * as THREE from 'three';\nconst scene = new THREE.Scene();"},{"heading":"2. Renderer, Scene & Camera","content":"Configure `WebGLRenderer`, set size and append to DOM; camera types like `PerspectiveCamera` or `OrthographicCamera`.","code":"const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth/window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);\nconst renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer();\nrenderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);\ndocument.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);"},{"heading":"3. Geometry & Meshes","content":"Use built-in geometries (`BoxGeometry`, `SphereGeometry`), combine with materials (`MeshBasicMaterial`, `MeshStandardMaterial`).","code":"const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry();\nconst material = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x00ff00 });\nconst cube = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);\nscene.add(cube);"},{"heading":"4. Lighting","content":"Add different light types: `AmbientLight`, `DirectionalLight`, `PointLight`, `SpotLight`.","code":"const light = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 1);\nscene.add(light);"},{"heading":"5. Animation Loop","content":"Use `requestAnimationFrame`, update object parameters, and re-render.","code":"function animate() {\n  requestAnimationFrame(animate);\n  cube.rotation.x += 0.01;\n  cube.rotation.y += 0.01;\n  renderer.render(scene, camera);\n}\nanimate();"},{"heading":"6. Controls & Interaction","content":"Integrate `OrbitControls` for camera manipulation.","links":[{"text":"OrbitControls Demo","href":"https://threejs.org/docs/#examples/en/controls/OrbitControls"}],"code":"import { OrbitControls } from 'three/examples/jsm/controls/OrbitControls.js';\nconst controls = new OrbitControls(camera, renderer.domElement);"},{"heading":"7. Textures & Materials","content":"Load and apply textures using `TextureLoader`; work with `NormalMap`, `RoughnessMap`, etc.","code":"const loader = new THREE.TextureLoader();\nloader.load('texture.jpg', tex => {\n  material.map = tex;\n  material.needsUpdate = true;\n});"},{"heading":"8. Models & Loaders","content":"Import external models using loaders (`GLTFLoader`, `OBJLoader`).","links":[{"text":"GLTFLoader Guide","href":"https://threejs.org/docs/#examples/en/loaders/GLTFLoader"}],"code":"import { GLTFLoader } from 'three/examples/jsm/loaders/GLTFLoader.js';\nnew GLTFLoader().load('model.gltf', gltf => scene.add(gltf.scene));"},{"heading":"9. Post-Processing","content":"Use `EffectComposer`, `RenderPass`, and effects like bloom, depth-of-field.","links":[{"text":"Post-processing examples","href":"https://threejs.org/examples/#webgl_postprocessing_unreal_bloom"}]},{"heading":"10. Shadows","content":"Enable shadows (`renderer.shadowMap.enabled`, `castShadow`, `receiveShadow`).","code":"renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true;\ncube.castShadow = true;\nfloor.receiveShadow = true;"},{"heading":"11. Performance Optimization","content":"Use instanced meshes, frustum culling, LOD, texture compression."},{"heading":"12. Custom Shaders","content":"Write GLSL via `ShaderMaterial` or extend `RawShaderMaterial`.","code":"const material = new THREE.ShaderMaterial({ vertexShader: vs, fragmentShader: fs });"},{"heading":"13. Physics Integration","content":"Integrate physics engines like `cannon-es`, `ammo.js` for realistic simulation."},{"heading":"14. VR & AR","content":"Use `WebXRManager` for immersive 3D experiences.","links":[{"text":"Three.js WebXR example","href":"https://threejs.org/examples/#webxr_vr_orbital_controls"}]},{"heading":"15. Data Visualization","content":"Plot 3D graphs, point clouds, heatmaps with Three.js."},{"heading":"16. Scene Management","content":"Organize with Layers, Groups, and scene hierarchy."},{"heading":"17. Exporting & Serialization","content":"Save scenes and assets (e.g. using `GLTFExporter`)."},{"heading":"18. Testing & Debugging","content":"Use Chrome DevTools for WebGL debugging; verify geometry/normals."},{"heading":"19. Community & Resources","content":"Rely on threejs.org, examples, and community forums like StackOverflow."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep geometry counts low\n- Dispose of unused resources\n- Reuse materials/textures\n- Profile with Stats.js"}],"related":["new-relic-roadmap","linux-roadmap","svelte-roadmap","django-roadmap","unity-roadmap"]},{"slug":"p5js-roadmap","title":"p5.js Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master p5.js in 2025 with this roadmap covering drawing basics, interaction, animation, data, and creative coding practices.","sections":[{"heading":"What is p5.js?","content":"p5.js is a JavaScript creative coding library that simplifies drawing, animation, and interaction—great for learning graphics and arts."},{"heading":"Why p5.js?","content":"It has a beginner-friendly API, integrates easily with web pages, and is heavily used for educational and artistic projects."},{"heading":"1. Getting Started","content":"Include p5.js via CDN or npm (`npm install p5`), then define `setup()` and `draw()`."},{"heading":"2. Basic Shapes & Drawing","content":"Use `rect()`, `ellipse()`, `line()`, `background()` for canvas drawing.","code":"function setup() { createCanvas(400, 400); }\nfunction draw() { background(220); ellipse(200, 200, 50, 50); }"},{"heading":"3. Color & Styles","content":"Control colors with `fill()`, `stroke()`, `background()`, and HSB/RGB modes."},{"heading":"4. Animation Loop","content":"Use variables and `draw()` per-frame updates; use `frameRate()` to control speed."},{"heading":"5. Mouse & Keyboard Interaction","content":"Use `mousePressed()`, `mouseX`, `keyIsDown()` for interactivity."},{"heading":"6. Transformations","content":"Translate, rotate, scale using `push()` and `pop()`."},{"heading":"7. Working with Images & Media","content":"Load images and audio with `loadImage()`, `createCapture()`, `loadSound()`."},{"heading":"8. Data Visualization","content":"Plot charts using `beginShape()`, `vertex()`, and arrays of data."},{"heading":"9. Object-Oriented Sketches","content":"Use JS classes to organize visuals and behaviors."},{"heading":"10. Particle Systems","content":"Build particle effects using arrays of objects and vector math."},{"heading":"11. DOM Integration","content":"Combine with HTML elements and p5.dom library for UI controls."},{"heading":"12. Sound Interaction","content":"Visualize audio with FFT, amplitude, playback controls."},{"heading":"13. Exporting & Saving","content":"Use `saveCanvas()`, `saveFrames()` to export art."},{"heading":"14. Responsive Sketches","content":"Use `resizeCanvas()` and detect mobile orientation."},{"heading":"15. Libraries & Extensions","content":"Use p5.sound, p5.dom, p5.createloop, p5.gui, etc."},{"heading":"16. Collaboration & Remixing","content":"Share via openProcessing, embed sketches, and remix others' work."},{"heading":"17. Performance Tuning","content":"Minimize draw complexity, leverage `noLoop()` and `instanceMode`."},{"heading":"18. Learning Resources","content":"Use p5js.org, The Coding Train videos, and official reference."},{"heading":"19. Testing & Debugging","content":"Use `console.log()` and browser DOM inspection tools."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep code modular\n- Use classes and modules\n- Manage draw loops efficiently\n- Leverage contextColor/alpha for layering"}],"related":["prometheus-roadmap","mongodb-roadmap","netlify-roadmap","sanity-io-roadmap","strapi-roadmap"]},{"slug":"chartjs-roadmap","title":"Chart.js Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Chart.js in 2025 with this roadmap covering installation, chart types, configuration, customization, interactivity, and performance optimization.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Chart.js?","content":"Chart.js is a simple yet flexible JavaScript charting library for building responsive, animated charts on the web using the HTML5 canvas element."},{"heading":"Why Chart.js?","content":"It offers easy setup, a clean API, various chart types, animations, and plugins, making it ideal for adding visual data representations to web apps."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install via npm (`npm install chart.js`) or include via CDN script tag.","code":"import { Chart, registerables } from 'chart.js';\nChart.register(...registerables);\nconst ctx = document.getElementById('myChart');"},{"heading":"2. Basic Chart Creation","content":"Create a basic line, bar, or pie chart by passing data and config.","code":"new Chart(ctx, { type: 'bar', data: {...}, options: {...} });"},{"heading":"3. Chart Types","content":"Master line, bar, radar, doughnut, polar area, bubble, scatter, and mixed charts."},{"heading":"4. Configuration & Options","content":"Customize axes, scales, tooltips, legends, and transitions via `options` object."},{"heading":"5. Data Handling & Updates","content":"Dynamically update charts with `.update()`, `.addData()`, and reactive frameworks.","code":"chart.data.datasets[0].data.push(newValue);\nchart.update();"},{"heading":"6. Styling & Themes","content":"Change colors, fonts, border styles, and use custom gradients or CSS variables."},{"heading":"7. Interactivity","content":"Handle click, hover events using `onClick`, `hover`, and `tooltip.callbacks`."},{"heading":"8. Animation Control","content":"Use `animation.duration`, `easing`, and custom animation callbacks."},{"heading":"9. Plugins & Extensions","content":"Use built-in plugins or create custom plugins for annotation, data labels, zooming."},{"heading":"10. Responsiveness","content":"Use `responsive: true` with aspect ratio and resizing hooks."},{"heading":"11. Performance Optimization","content":"Limit data points, use decimation, canvas streaming, and avoid re-creating charts frequently."},{"heading":"12. Export & Download","content":"Generate and export chart images with `toBase64Image()`."},{"heading":"13. Using with Frameworks","content":"Integrate with React, Vue, Angular using wrapper components like `react-chartjs-2` or Vue ChartJS."},{"heading":"14. TypeScript Support","content":"Leverage built-in TypeScript types or community definitions."},{"heading":"15. Accessibility & ARIA","content":"Add ARIA attributes, keyboard navigation, and screen-reader descriptions."},{"heading":"16. Unit Testing Charts","content":"Use Jest with `canvas-mock` and snapshot plugins."},{"heading":"17. Dashboard Integration","content":"Combine multiple charts, shared tooltips, synchronized zoom."},{"heading":"18. Real‑time Data","content":"Stream data via WebSocket and update charts in real-time."},{"heading":"19. Common Pitfalls","content":"Avoid memory leaks by destroying charts, reuse instances and reset data."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Modularize chart configs\n- Use plugins responsibly\n- Keep datasets minimal\n- Profile using browser dev tools"}],"related":["angular-roadmap","nodejs-roadmap","react-roadmap","grafana-roadmap","storybook-roadmap"]},{"slug":"nextauthjs-roadmap","title":"NextAuth.js Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master NextAuth.js in 2025 with this roadmap covering setup, providers, JWT/session strategies, callbacks, database integration, and security best practices.","sections":[{"heading":"What is NextAuth.js?","content":"NextAuth.js is a complete open-source authentication solution for Next.js applications supporting OAuth, email/passwordless, JWT, and database adapters."},{"heading":"Why NextAuth.js?","content":"It simplifies auth flows in Next.js, supports multiple providers, secure session handling, and integrates well with database adapters."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install via `npm install next-auth`, create `[...nextauth].js` route API."},{"heading":"2. Configuring Providers","content":"Use OAuth providers like Google, GitHub, or credentials provider.","code":"import NextAuth from 'next-auth';\nimport GitHubProvider from 'next-auth/providers/github';\nexport default NextAuth({ providers: [ GitHubProvider({ clientId, clientSecret }) ] });"},{"heading":"3. Session vs JWT Strategies","content":"Use session cookies (default) or `jwt: true` sessions."},{"heading":"4. Callbacks & Events","content":"Customize session, JWT, sign-in behavior using `callbacks` config."},{"heading":"5. Database Adapters","content":"Use built-in adapters for Prisma, TypeORM, MongoDB, etc."},{"heading":"6. Securing Routes","content":"Protect Next.js pages/API routes using `getSession()` or `useSession()`."},{"heading":"7. Custom Pages","content":"Override default sign-in, sign-out, error pages, and themes."},{"heading":"8. Credentials Provider","content":"Implement email/password login with custom verify logic."},{"heading":"9. Email/Passwordless Sign-in","content":"Send magic links via email provider."},{"heading":"10. Account Linking & Multiple Providers","content":"Link social accounts to same user profile."},{"heading":"11. CSRF Protection & Security","content":"Built-in CSRF tokens, ensure HTTPS in production."},{"heading":"12. Handling Callbacks and Redirects","content":"Use `redirect` and `session` callbacks to control flow."},{"heading":"13. Token Encoding & Session Storage","content":"Customize `jwt.encode`, `jwt.decode`, or session storage mechanisms."},{"heading":"14. Accessing Token in Client & Server","content":"Use `getToken()` in API routes or client hooks."},{"heading":"15. TypeScript Integration","content":"Use type augmentation for `Session`, `User`, and callback contexts."},{"heading":"16. Testing Authentication","content":"Mock NextAuth.js for unit tests, use `next-auth/testing` utilities."},{"heading":"17. Deploying Auth","content":"Configure environment variables, providers, and secrets for Vercel, Netlify."},{"heading":"18. Monitoring & Analytics","content":"Track sign-ins, errors using NextAuth events or external logging."},{"heading":"19. Scaling & Performance","content":"Use JWT sessions for stateless scaling, optimize DB calls."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Keep secrets secure\n- Validate callback logic\n- Handle errors gracefully\n- Regularly rotate tokens"}],"related":["mongodb-roadmap","python-roadmap","metamask-roadmap","p5js-roadmap","github-roadmap"]},{"slug":"passportjs-roadmap","title":"Passport.js Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Passport.js in 2025 with this roadmap covering authentication, strategies, session handling, and best practices for secure Node.js apps.","sections":[{"heading":"What is Passport.js?","content":"Passport.js is a flexible, modular authentication middleware for Node.js, supporting various strategies (OAuth, JWT, local, etc.)."},{"heading":"Why Passport.js?","content":"It provides a consistent authentication interface, easy strategy swapping, and seamless integration with Express apps."},{"heading":"1. Installation & Setup","content":"Install with npm: `npm install passport` and desired strategies (e.g. `passport-local`).","code":"const passport = require('passport');\napp.use(passport.initialize());\napp.use(passport.session());"},{"heading":"2. Local Strategy","content":"Use `passport-local` for email/password login with usernameField mapping.","code":"passport.use(new LocalStrategy(\n  (username, password, done) => { /* verify user */ }\n));"},{"heading":"3. Serialize & Deserialize User","content":"Control session data stored in cookies.","code":"passport.serializeUser((user, done) => done(null, user.id));\npassport.deserializeUser((id, done) => {/* fetch user */});"},{"heading":"4. OAuth Strategies","content":"Use `passport-google-oauth20`, `passport-facebook`, etc.","code":"passport.use(new GoogleStrategy({/* config */}, (token, profile, done) => { /* callback */ }));"},{"heading":"5. JWT Strategy","content":"Use `passport-jwt` for stateless token-based auth.","code":"passport.use(new JwtStrategy(opts, (jwt_payload, done) => { /* verify token */ }));"},{"heading":"6. Route Protection","content":"Protect routes with `passport.authenticate()` middleware.","code":"app.get('/profile', passport.authenticate('jwt', { session: false }), (req, res) => { res.json(req.user); });"},{"heading":"7. Session Management","content":"Configure `express-session` when using sessions, secure cookies, and session store."},{"heading":"8. Social Login Flow","content":"Set up OAuth login redirect, callback endpoints, and user provisioning."},{"heading":"9. Custom Callbacks","content":"Use `passReqToCallback` for access to request in the strategy."},{"heading":"10. Linking Multiple Auth Methods","content":"Allow users to link JWT, local, and social logins using multiple strategies."},{"heading":"11. Error Handling & Feedback","content":"Customize error messages and failures via `failureRedirect`, flash messages."},{"heading":"12. Role-Based Access Control","content":"Add middleware after authentication to check user roles/permissions."},{"heading":"13. Session Logout","content":"Terminate sessions and tokens correctly with `req.logout()`."},{"heading":"14. Security Best Practices","content":"Use HTTPS, secure cookies, rotate secrets, protect against store misconfig."},{"heading":"15. API Token Refresh","content":"Implement refresh token logic for JWT strategies."},{"heading":"16. Testing Auth Flows","content":"Mock Passport in tests with `sinon` or test strategies directly."},{"heading":"17. TypeScript Integration","content":"Use `@types/passport` and strong typing for sessions and user properties."},{"heading":"18. Logging & Analytics","content":"Log login attempts, provider info, and failures for audit."},{"heading":"19. Performance & Caching","content":"Cache sessions, minimize DB calls in `deserializeUser`."},{"heading":"20. Best Practices","content":"- Organize strategies modularly\n- Keep auth simple but flexible\n- Ensure proper failure handling\n- Rotate credentials regularly"}],"related":["php-roadmap","langchain-roadmap","swift-roadmap","react-roadmap","apache-roadmap"]},{"slug":"strapi-roadmap","title":"Strapi Roadmap: A Complete Guide [2025 Updated]","description":"Master Strapi in 2025 with this roadmap covering headless CMS setup, content modeling, authentication,